  "text": "(5) (6) (7) Figure 1 : The Gorille data flow extract from it its control flow graph, we abstract (2) it (we remove sequential instructions and some jumps), and finally, we cut it into small pieces (3), next called sites (graphs of size around 20). In a second step, we run the code it in a safe environment (5) which is made invisible to malware as much as possible. More precisely, we collect at any steps of the computation the value of registers (in particular the instruction pointer) and RAM cells. Then, we apply a self-modification analysis (6) of the runs which outputs RAM snapshots-next called wavescorresponding to key stones in the malware temporal evolution (see [CITATION_1] ). Then, for each wave, we build their control flow graphs (7) which we will abstract in a simpler form as explained above. In a third step, we reassemble static and dynamic analysis. We sum up the chain in Figure 1 .",
